    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-10-02T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-10-02T06:00:00-05:00" n="354"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d354">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6231/415: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-10-02T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 2, 1934—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received October 2—10:05
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>191. Commercial Attaché has been approached by highly influential Government
                    officials keenly desirous of concluding private barter agreements for American
                    lumber especially pitch pine, plywood, Oregon pine, Douglas fir. Handicapped by
                    existing American tariff schedules notably barbed wire, bale ties, wire fencing
                    and wire rope, they inquire as to possibility of lowering these independently of
                    general commercial treaty negotiations.</p>
                <p>While they would be willing to offer reciprocal reductions, these not of
                    significance in view of German import restrictions; indeed only advantage to us
                    lies in possibility of concluding barter agreements otherwise blocked.
                    Commercial Attaché would appreciate cable as to answer he should make.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodd</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
